sentence_array_final=[['   Wall Street extended a global stock selloff Thursday with the Dow industrials tumbling more than 200 points for a second straight day', 147.10544627938592], ['The Dow Jones industrial average, which plunged 23790 points on Wednesday, fell an additional 21009, or by 27 percent, to close at 7,63253', 149.11764366542945], ['Broader market indicators also sank sharply in heavy trading', 63.03543908074561], ['Bank and technology stocks were particularly hard hit', 57.021708600348475], ['The selling spree, amid worries about shrinking corporate profits and fears of new financial crises, left the Dow 183 percent, or more than 1,700 points, below the all-time high of 9,33797 reached on July 17', 219.16544917698468], ["It was getting closer to the low of 7,400 that was reached during trading Sept 1, before Wall Street's best-known indicator began a comeback bid that brought it above 8,100 as recently as Monday", 202.11880212488225], ["The Dow's 124 percent slide in the third quarter, which ended Wednesday, was its worst quarterly performance in eight years", 132.08382396095715], ['It now is 35 percent below where it began this year', 54.05763480856818], ["Stock prices earlier plunged in Asia, with Tokyo shares falling 16 percent to a new 12-year low, and shares were falling sharply in Europe, where Germany's central bank left interest rates unchanged", 217.18185208320477], ['Blue chips in London sank 31 percent to close at new lows for the year, while the key index in Frankfurt, Germany, closed down 55 percent and the main indicator in Paris was off 5 percent', 207.14707745470918], ['The selloff in stocks has sent a flood of money into US Treasury securities, a traditional haven in times of uncertainty', 129.0551203016779], ['Yields on 30-year Treasury bonds fell further below 5 percent Thursday, reaching levels unseen for long-term government bonds since 1967', 146.10701736332587], ['Traders were alarmed to see prices on the New York Stock Exchange nosedive 29 percent on Wednesday, even though the Federal Reserve had lowered a key interest rate one-quarter percentage point on Tuesday', 226.14262421559323], ['Some traders were disappointed that the cut was not deeper amid fears a go-slow approach would not do enough to counter the economic crises that have swept through Asia and Russia and are threatening Latin America', 229.08607486115181], ["The smaller-than-expected lowering of interest rates by the US Federal Reserve has a chain reaction,'' said Lee Won-ho, an analyst at Samsung Securities Co in Seoul, South Korea, where the main stock index fell by 15 percent", 254.15617886887537], ["It is affecting Wall Street, the Japanese market, ours and others''", 74.04513434873218], ['The managing director of the International Monetary Fund, Michel Camdessus, on Thursday said the Fed made the right decision in cutting rates and that global powers now must push for stronger growth to offset steep recessions in Asia and Russia', 270.0951569533128], ['Asked why stock markets, particularly in the United States, have reacted so negatively to the Fed rate cut, Camdessus said he believed confidence will soon be restored, especially if financial leaders show resolve in their discussions over the next week', 268.1071303595003], ["There also are worries about where the next financial market crisis may erupt after last week's dlrs 36 billion private bailout of Long-Term Capital Management LP of Greenwich, Connecticut", 209.07766312706013], ['In addition, investors worldwide worry that the downturn on Wall Street could signal a possible slowdown in economic growth  a bad omen for the many foreign companies dependent on exports to the huge US market', 224.08491814525163], ["There's a psychological impact overall, but there's also a direct impact on companies like Sony and TDK which derive a high percentage of their earnings from overseas markets,'' said Pelham Smithers, a stock strategist in Tokyo at ING Baring Securities Japan Ltd A new survey in Japan said confidence among small- and medium-sized businesses about the economy plunged to its worst level since the Bank of Japan began the quarterly samplings in 1967", 491.2539057143264], ['   If the Communist Party has its way  and it has been planning for months  millions of Russians will take to the streets on Wednesday for some of the biggest demonstrations in years', 194.08584717682461], ['But now that Communists or politicians with the Communist stamp of approval are running the country and its economy the question is what the marchers will be demonstrating against', 186.07764592376375], ['President Boris Yeltsin and his economic advisers were easy targets two months ago', 90.04362204210048], ['But Yeltsin seems but a shadow of himself today, and his advisers are gone', 80.04063832877242], ['The Communists, who have undergone a sort of resurgence by playing on the discontent, are working hard to cast themselves as outsiders in the government that they help run  and to keep the focus of the protests on Wednesday on Yeltsin and his policies', 264.1059119082521], ['Even that strategy may backfire, however, because discontent over Yeltsin does not necessarily translate into support for his predecessors', 143.0553003821264], ['An adviser to the Communist Party leader, Gennadi Zyuganov, made headlines not long ago when he called the new government bourgeois', 143.07463278090935], ["The characterization was striking, because the new prime minister, Yevgeny Primakov, was one of Zyuganov's top choices for the post", 143.03008336887922], ['The deputy prime minister in charge of the economy, Yuri Maslyukov, is a Communist Party figure who once headed Gosplan, the infamous central-planning program that helped bring the Soviet Union to ruin', 225.09358320386255], ["We don't have slogans that are aimed against the government,'' the first secretary of the Moscow Communist Party committee, Alexander Kuvayev, said in a recent interview", 186.09302722680926], ['All the slogans are aimed against the president and the economic course of the country', 91.04092407133268], ["Only the president can fully be blamed for the course that has brought the country to this situation''", 106.02921664732543], ["Anger over Russia's fate, and their own, is drawing some Russians back to Soviet-style slogans and old-style hostility toward capitalism", 146.0642523410302], ['The ardently pro-Communist newspaper Sovietskaya Rossiya devoted most of its front page on Thursday to what it said were the results of a contest among readers for protest slogans', 192.0777974955773], ["The entries ranged from catchy to kitschy, from, Legislator, official, banker  study the Constitution the exam is Oct 7,'' to,  Imperialist", 147.04308843865937], ["Help Russia return the exported capital, and we will pay the debts at once''", 84.02175283565037], ['Russia has seen nothing approaching this sort of economic chaos and despair since 1993, when hyperinflation swept the economy', 131.0529301755606], ['There is no real way of knowing whether the latest travails will produce huge and ugly crowds or small, peaceful ones', 126.04619530474092], ['A deputy editor and political analyst at a newsweekly, Itogi, Masha Lipman, said the situation was not unlike that of 1993, when Yeltsin sought, and won, a popular mandate in a referendum', 203.081094308951], ['He used it to dissolve the Communist-dominated Parliament and increase his own power', 95.047847188778], ["That led to an autumn showdown, the shelling of Parliament by tanks and the total defeat, for the time being, of Yeltsin's legislative opponents", 154.05299676114117], ["You can interpret this demonstration as a Communist mandate, but I don't think they will act like Yeltsin,'' Ms Lipman said", 135.0826095946645], ["Support for the Communists is at its smallest level, maybe 20 percent''", 75.03358314799459], ['In a survey of 1,714 people that was released last week the All-Russian Public Opinion Center said that nearly half the population supported the idea of demonstrations against Yeltsin, but that barely one-tenth were likely to participate in any way', 268.10488571472035], ["Nobody is interested in any sort of struggle,'' Yuri Levada, who heads the center, said in an interview", 111.05367578102857], ['This is mainly a general expression of a great wave of distrust of authorities, mainly the president', 106.04052675771968], ["He's the great scapegoat for all our sins''", 46.020664447074594], ['There seems to be little enthusiasm for demonstrations of any sort', 71.04096663709548], ["Only a few thousand people turned out Sunday for the fifth anniversary of the shelling of Parliament and Yeltsin's subsequent triumph over the Communists", 166.0682417751967], ['The Communist Party and the Federation of Independent Russian Unions, a leftist organization that says it is the main sponsor of the protests, predict that 9 million Russians will participate on Wednesday', 228.0940145369527], ['The government has vowed to keep order without resorting to force', 70.01266105938045], ['But it is concerned enough that it has summoned 11,000 police officers to patrol Moscow and 6,000 military troops to intervene if violence erupts', 153.056177213259], ['Protests since 1993 have generally been tepid, a deep-seated feeling here', 78.0392167475378], ['Some demonstrations last week, more or less practice runs, hinted at similarly dampened marches this year', 107.04739131757839], ["   Ukraine's parliament on Friday refused to approve President Leonid Kuchma's decree establishing a state fund to compensate people for savings lost in banks", 172.1810470375881], ['Deputies voted 240-47 to prepare a revised version of the decree and debate it later in the month', 105.1236338577029], ['They must consider the decree by Oct 10, or else it automatically takes effect under the constitution', 107.1222073329493], ['Leftist factions, which voted against the proposed legislation, said it would not fully guarantee the return of savings lost during the financial instability that has recently hit Ukraine', 196.19650022874683], ['The fund Kuchma proposed to establish would have accumulated money in a special National Bank account and repay people in case the bank they kept their savings in went bankrupt or became insolvent', 211.20678584264834], ['Although the decree provided for compensation of deposits amounting only to 500 hryvna dlrs 147 at the current exchange rate, its authors said it would cover more than 90 percent of Ukrainians who keep their money in banks', 234.22607314424204], ['The measure was meant to prevent mass withdrawals of deposits that most Ukrainian banks have already experienced as people, scared by the fall of the national currency and the turmoil in neighboring Russia, started to stock up on food, clothing and household goods', 275.1991942543272], ['Government officials say that Ukrainians have recently withdrawn at least 10 percent of the 3 billion hryvna dlrs 882 million they deposited in banks', 157.1532664693804], ["   Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov said Saturday that the economic crisis would not bring an end to the government's program of privatizing state property", 168.05338169126577], ["Privatization will be accomplished for growth of production, growth of investment and growth of production effectiveness through renewal of major funds,'' Primakov said during a meeting of Western businessmen", 217.1361969737305], ["We shall conduct privatization so that it serves the interests of the people, the state, and business,'' he said, according to the ITAR-Tass news agency", 161.0913579482539], ["Primakov reassured the businessmen, members of the prime minister's consultive council on foreign investment in Russia, that the government had no plans to ban the circulation of US dollars in Russia", 214.09223987189003], ['But, he said, the government would take steps to staunch the flow of dollars from Russia', 97.04998544412237], ["Responding to media reports of a government economic plan that would prohibit Russians from buying US dollars and other foreign currency, Primakov said the reports absolutely do not correspond to reality,'' ITAR-Tass quoted him as saying", 253.13078073031005], ["He said there was no need to regulate the influx of dollars into Russia, but the government should take steps to prevent what he called the dollar drain''", 164.07964401787362], ['Russian companies stashed about dlrs 25 billion outside the country in September alone, the Interfax news agency reported Friday, quoting central bank figures', 168.06602480196898], ["Primakov said foreign investors are the force'' that will help Russia to minimize its losses from the current economic crisis", 138.0582032982199], ["We are very much interested in foreign investments, especially in ones that go into the real production sector,'' Primakov said, according to Interfax", 162.10106626806004], ["We need a continuous dialogue with foreign investors, without whom it will be difficult for us to overcome the current difficulties''", 142.0723085088973], ['He said Russia wanted long-term investments', 48.027995549654456], ["Foreign capital has been coming to the country via short-term operations,'' Primakov said", 96.05289177821949], ["This, he said, is not to our liking or yours''", 49.023596278161385], ['Viktor Gerashchenko, the central bank chairman, said on Friday that the government must act to stem the flow of dollars from Russia', 146.04809210506738], ['Gerashchenko and Finance Minister Mikhail Zadornov were in Washington Saturday for the annual meeting of the International Monetary Fund, where they plan to spell out the measures Russia is taking to bail out its finance system', 252.0957042844211], ["Russia wants the IMF to release the second dlrs 43 billion installment of a loan that was approved in July, a month before the country's economy crashed and the government effectively defaulted on its foreign loans", 228.0721175721073], ['IMF officials have said they want the Russian government to come up with a sound economic program before the installment is given, and have made it clear that currency controls and boosting the money supply by printing rubles are not acceptable', 257.0539483104461], ['   The United States is disappointed by the economic confusion within the new Russian government of Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov, said Secretary of State Madeleine Albright on Friday, and she warned Russia about the dangers of an anti-Western policy', 282.1419935312363], ["In her first comprehensive review of US-Russian relations since Primakov was confirmed as prime minister last month, Albright said Washington was deeply concerned'' about Russia's direction and did not think the crisis there would soon abate", 263.1229820453765], ["We have heard a lot of talk in recent days about printing new money, indexing wages, imposing price and capital controls and restoring state management of parts of the economy,'' she told the US-Russia Business Council in Chicago", 244.12050314995253], ["We can only wonder if some members of Primakov's team understand the basic arithmetic of the global economy''", 117.04903379854983], ['While praising Primakov, once her counterpart when he was foreign minister, as a pragmatist able to cooperate on key issues with Washington, she had harsh words of warning for him', 191.12867126645264], ["Our initial reaction to some of the direction he's going in has not been particularly positive,'' she said, adding, The question now is whether that cooperation can continue''", 184.1054025669526], ['The United States must keep up its aid to Russia but is adjusting it to promote the building of democracy and student exchanges as well as arms control, Albright said', 181.11153756613714], ['Washington does not favor more direct aid', 45.02689381730464], ["More big bailouts are not by themselves going to restore investor confidence in Russia,'' she said", 105.08027969350282], ["In the long run, the gap between Russia's needs and its resources must be met not by foreign bailouts but by foreign investment''", 139.05787813572107], ["Albright sharply criticized as self-defeating the many voices in Russia who want to shift the emphasis in Russia's interaction with America and our allies from one of partnership to one of assertiveness, opposition and defiance for its own stake''", 264.12255946205045], ["Russia could not stand alone in the world, she said, and the United States' ability to help Russians help themselves will go from being merely very, very difficult to being absolutely impossible''", 212.13773432221737], ["At the same time, she said, Washington would not assume the worst, for there are still plenty of people in Russia who will fight against turning back the clock''", 173.08745481832048], ["And she urged the world  and American critics  to be patient with the workings of the democratic process in Russia'' and not start each day by taking a census of reformers in the Kremlin,'' a census that American officials themselves promoted before President Boris Yeltsin dismissed the previous government", 331.16879775782115], ['While Moscow may continue to oppose any NATO use of force against Serbian forces in the southern province of Kosovo, Albright said, NATO must be prepared to act regardless', 193.1243023546469], ['   In a season of crashing banks, plunging rubles, bouncing paychecks, failing cropsand rotating governments, maybe it is not the ultimate insult', 150.04423159541497], ['But the nation that bore Tolstoy and Chekhov, and still regards a well-written letter as a labor of love, is buckling a little this week, because it can no longer wish good health to Baba Anya in Omsk', 221.07767777474666], ['The Post Office is broke', 30.05575028344733], ["In 60 of the country's 89 statelike regions, more than 1,000 mail cars have been sidetracked, many stuffed with up to 18 tons of letters, newspapers and parcels", 171.08969860951808], ["The state Railway Ministry refuses to carry more mail until the Post Office makes good on some 210 million rubles in old bills  about 13 million in today's dollars, or 35 million in dollars six weeks ago", 220.18623487809688], ["Air mail, which amounts to one of every four or five letters, was also suspended at one of Moscow's major airports until this week, when the Post Office coughed up 5 million rubles for old bills", 207.16747250813214], ['A second airport is still demanding 3 million rubles for past-due debts', 75.03919224561031], ['So much mail is backed up that post offices in Moscow and elsewhere have simply stopped accepting out-of-town mail, except for areas that can be easily reached by truck', 177.14326421768416], ['Delivery schedules have fallen weeks, and perhaps months, behind', 66.02105480540669], ["The situation is really extraordinary,'' said Vladimir Sherekhov, the deputy chief of mail service administration in the government's Communications Committee", 171.08255104444063], ["We've never had anything like this before''", 44.02096658438791], ['Maybe the Post Office has been lucky', 43.05329446264052], ['Extraordinary is the rule elsewhere in Russia', 50.01922311788015], ["Until Friday, the lower house of Parliament was preparing to sue the government for failure to provide soap, heat, toilet paper and copy-machine paper in the legislature's monumental downtown offices", 213.0516222059086], ["It turned out that politicians had exhausted their funds by cutting short their recess and returning to address the nation's economic crisis", 147.0315743189261], ["Earlier in the week, officials said Russia's Arctic shipping routes may close next month because half the nation's icebreakers are in disrepair and there is no money to fix them", 189.05157719160326], ['The oldest of the ships is so ancient that its nickname is Granny', 71.02846649967657], ['Such anecdotal evidence that Russia is losing its wheels, like one of its old, ill-maintained Volga sedans, is everywhere', 131.04876946361196], ['But oddly, real signs of public distress are not particularly common, perhaps because the system rarely seems to shed a part as big as a postal system', 160.0548458755897], ['If the US', 13.001997448865485], ['Postal Service is increasingly a pipeline for sweepstakes notices and bills, the Russian Post Office still holds a special place in the national conversation', 173.10166769055147], ['Russians still write letters to each other, frequently and fervently, and many in remote regions get their news through the mail', 136.074243648193], ['Millions use the mails to ship canned goods and other provisions to needy relatives and friends in faraway areas, an especially vital service in winter', 162.04286628006605], ['And in the last few years, the Post Office has become a vehicle for a growing mail-order trade in books, clothes and other catalog items not readily available outside big cities', 192.12154147661158], ['Exactly why all this has rumbled to a halt is in some dispute', 64.02783640278696], ['What is clear is that the Post Office and the Railway Ministry both suffer from what ails every Russian venture, private and public alike Nobody pays his bills', 176.12141743278602], ['The state Railway Ministry complains that it is continually stiffed by customers who believe the railroads are honor-bound to carry freight whether they are paid or not', 177.09211794212823], ['The government has specified nearly 40 categories of freight which the railroads must carry for next to nothing', 118.05028542013287], ["Among the biggest deadbeats are the power ministries''  the military and interior departments  which did not pay during Soviet times and feel little need to pay now", 176.0397349874212], ["It's a psychology formed during the socialist period,'' said Tatiana Pashkova, the deputy spokeswoman for the ministry, and the same situation exists with the Post Office", 183.09409632981942], ["We've been in dispute for a very long time", 45.01931624978446], ['Always we try to understand their differences', 48.01347748106531], ["But we can't carry cargo for free''", 39.02041158302369], ['No kidding, says the Post Office It, too, is owed 200 million rubles by government agencies, and is barred from raising rates even though freight costs are outstripping revenues', 184.1130235609627], ['Moreover, the Post Office is also required by the government to carry some forms of mail, such as pension checks, at reduced rates', 140.12361779605996], ["Officials at the state Communications Department say they also suspect an ulterior motive in the railroads' actions a struggle to dominate the thriving mail-order business", 183.09363720964254], ["Here's competition between us and the railroads for the delivery of parcels, and I think decisions made by the railroads are mainly explained by this competition,'' Sherekhov said", 186.0801842892967], ["They blame us for carrying some commercial cargoes instead of mail''", 71.0532146918972], ["The Railways Ministry's spokeswoman, Ms Pashkova, said such commercial cargoes'' are indeed a problem, but only because the railroads know that the Post Office has already gotten cash to transport the packages", 227.1298227538604], ['The railroads are still waiting for their share of that money, she said', 74.03618951307162], ['In the meantime, the situation has come to a boil', 53.01025186551243], ['In late September the railroads cut mail service in and out of Moscow, effectively decapitating the postal system and forcing officials to draft a fleet of trucks to move letters in and out of the city', 214.11285648364446], ['Hundreds of empty and full rail cars have clogged some local yards to the point where moving cars into position for unloading has become difficult', 155.0542507355668], ['At last count, 39 loaded cars were awaiting service at one yard', 67.03439306696319], ['And customers are getting angry', 34.01131110541843], ["We've gotten all kinds of complaints,'' said Viktor Salikov, a deputy in the Communications Department's mail shipping center", 137.07956377149807], ["People are even coming to us, searching for mail that was sent weeks ago''", 76.0515065774996], ["   President Leonid Kuchma called Friday for corrections'' to Ukraine's program of market reforms, but pledged that reforms would continue", 149.1013459241374], ["Kuchma did not elaborate in his comments to a group of Ukrainian economists, saying only that the changes were necessary because of the country's economic problems", 174.10221652536518], ['Kuchma urged the economists to come up with recommendations before a national meeting of economists in November, the Interfax news agency reported', 157.09956922948456], ['Ukraine has suffered economic problems since the 1991 collapse of the Soviet Union and it has been especially hard hit by the financial crisis in neighboring Russia, its main trading partner', 207.0901936383778], ['The Russian crisis has hurt bilateral trade, caused the Ukrainian currency to fall and led to a withdrawal of investors from Ukraine', 145.071856035105], ['In recent months, Kuchma has implemented some economic reforms by decree, prompting the International Monetary Fund to release the first installment of a long-awaited dlrs 22 billion loan', 207.09805202368497], ['Many reforms, however, remain stalled', 40.03218327686331], ['National Bank chairman Viktor Yushchenko was in Washington this week for consultations with IMF officials', 118.04781860147709], ['Yushchenko has warned that the bank would not spend its dwindling reserves to support the hryvna currency, but has avoided comments on the currency in recent days', 171.10856154335366], ['Kuchma met Friday with Yushchenko, Prime Minister Valery Pustovoitenko and other senior officials to discuss ways to stabilize the hryvna', 154.1091220859013], ["The government's press service said they focused on possible ways to keep the hryvna under 35 to the US dollar through the end of the year", 147.07430949788568], ['The hryvna has been trading at 34 to the dollar in recent days but trading has been limited', 98.08963167889178], ['There are wide expectations in Ukraine that the hryvna will fall even further, and Ukrainians have been stocking up on food, clothing and household goods to save their fast-devaluing money', 199.1141316412768], ["   Russia's new prime minister picked an unusual way to reassure the nation Thursday", 93.02742849610117], ['After two weeks of deliberations he announced that he still had no plan to rescue the country from its economic crisis', 124.05176166160877], ["I want to repeat once more  there is no program,'' Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov said", 96.02906215199188], ["It has yet to be worked out''", 33.017990139785994], ['In most nations such a statement might provoke alarm', 56.019878370106596], ["But Primakov was seeking to calm an anxious public that was worried that the Kremlin's cure could be worse than the disease", 135.05805268583657], ['It is not as if Russians do not have something to be concerned about', 74.02591212809783], ['Thursday Primakov convened a meeting of top aides to try to hammer out a strategy for overcoming the economic woes', 124.04716715530353], ["A main item on the agenda was the plan drafted by Yuri Maslyukov, a Communist and the government's senior policy maker on economic issues", 148.05142641798085], ["It did not take long for Maslyukov's plan to hit the street", 66.03488188827185], ['A newspaper, Kommersant Daily, published it in full Thursday morning', 76.03087375721546], ["Not surprisingly Maslyukov's plan calls for a greater state role in the economy, including controls on hard currency", 122.06528604963749], ["A new State Bank for Reconstruction and Development would be established using the nationalized assets'' of failed commercial banks", 150.04433644773795], ['Wages and pensions would be paid in two months, and the minimum wage would be indexed to inflation', 105.05610867992564], ['There would be huge tax cuts, a combination that suggested that the government was committed to printing additional money', 130.03424176434055], ['The exchange rate of the ruble would be set by the central bank, based on changes in inflation and the balance of payments', 127.04765317722644], ["Maslyukov's plan also implies that Russians would be able to buy dollars at exchanges through the country", 115.06436644880705], ['It stipulates that hard currency could enter the country only with special authorization', 94.02830408413594], ['Exporters would be required to sell most of their hard currency reserves', 78.03489986877108], ['That is an allusion to currency controls that sent shock waves through the Russian public', 95.03463761381555], ['Russians have come to treat the dollar as a second currency, and many people have squirreled away dollars as a hedge against inflation', 141.05430979063084], ["It is an obvious stupidity,'' Otto Latsis, a commentator with the newspaper Noviye Izvestiya, said", 110.03340172242001], ["People won't give their dollars away", 38.02097340299491], ["They will go to the black market if they need to''", 55.01318602668699], ["Yegor Gaidar, the former prime minister who favors free markets, said the plan was a war against the dollar'' and predicted that it would lead to a shortage of imports", 179.06546153678605], ['As the criticism grew, Primakov rushed to distance himself from the talk of currency controls', 99.04259877495156], ["The rumors of the state's becoming a monopolist on the inflow of hard currency into the country is nonsense,'' he said, asserting that the document published by Kommersant Daily was just one of six possible plans", 223.07514072474856], ['Primakov may be opposed to wildly unpopular currency controls', 67.04172662035644], ['He may be worried that the plan would would set off the panic buying of dollars, further depressing the ruble', 116.073543363813], ["Or he may simply be trying to keep his distance from Maslyukov's plan while Russia tries to wrangle its next disbursement, 43 billion, from the International Monetary Fund", 190.07870172954654], ["The particulars could be modified, but many people following the maneuvering say they believe that it represents the basic thrust of the government's thinking", 165.0461667839553], ["Primakov has called for greater state regulation and an expansion of the money supply, two themes of Maslyukov's plan", 122.0703827072969], ['The plan also has many similarities with the plan presented to the government by Gorbachev-era advisers', 108.05725025345248], ["We think it is close to being a final document,'' said the United Financial Group, a Russian investment business", 125.02678537435209], ['It is unclear how long Primakov can carry on without spelling out a detailed strategy', 92.04289453002946], ['The ousted tax chief, Boris Fyodorov, has argued that the IMF should not provide further aid until Primakov has taken tough measures to build a free market', 173.0645881977281], ["Primakov has, however, sought to turn that logic on its head, arguing that his government's economic strategy will depend on the fund's willingness to provide aid", 171.05299655244247], ["His aim appears to be to pressure the fund by implying that it will be the fund's fault if Russia is forced to default on its loans or take draconian measures at home", 179.07004696358715], ["Or as Primakov put it Thursday, without the fund's money, Russia will have to impose unpopular measures''", 116.04156069240165], ['   President Boris Yeltsin would respond strongly to any effort to prohibit Russians from buying foreign currencies, believing the move would be like bringing another Iron Curtain down on the country, his spokesman said Friday', 241.13327482256918], ["The president clearly understands that such a ban would be a clear violation of our rights  that would mean a return to the Iron Curtain in everyday life,'' said presidential spokesman Dmitry Yakushin", 216.10828928230563], ['The remarks came after media reports of a government economic plan in the works that would prohibit Russians from buying US dollars and other foreign currencies, and institute other strict economic controls, rolling back seven years of reforms', 258.12034665453314], ["Though government officials say such a plan is only one of six possibilities, Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov warned Thursday that he might be forced to take unpopular'' measures to rescue the Russian economy if it does not receive the next installment in a dlrs 226 billion loan from the International Monetary Fund", 344.11488303059764], ['Central Bank Chairman Viktor Gerashchenko and Finance Minister Mikhail Zadornov flew to Washington on Friday for negotiations with the IMF over the dlrs 43 billion installment', 200.071034835849], ['IMF officials have said they want the Russian government to come up with a sound economic program before the loan is given, and have made it clear that currency controls and boosting the money supply by printing rubles are not acceptable', 250.0701049764419], ["But Primakov said that the country's plan would be dependent on the IMF loan, not the other way around", 111.05952031938439], ['No short-term economic plan will be known for another three weeks, long after the IMF is set to make its decision, said First Deputy Prime Minister Vadim Gustov', 177.09685647160796], ["A draft version of the government's fourth-quarter budget would rely heavily on the IMF loan, the Kommersant newspaper said", 133.0558251104576], ['Without the loan, the government would have to engage in major deficit spending', 85.03220631984324], ['Calls for Soviet-style controls  part of the plan drafted by First Deputy Prime Minister Yuri Maslyukov and leaked to the press  have apparently created a rift within the Cabinet', 194.08395157786526], ["The plan drew heavy criticism from Zadornov, and Gerashchenko called the idea of banning foreign currency sales a mad idea''", 136.0846238980684], ["Meanwhile, Russia's stock market dropped by 5 percent to 388 Friday, but trading was so light the downward move meant little", 135.05581255932032], ['The stock market has continued to fall since the crisis hit Aug 17', 72.02546011213163], ["And tax collection was down in September, the result of the collapse in Russia's banking system, said Alexander Pochinok, head of the government's finance and credit department", 187.06676228071726], ['Revenues totaled 143 billion rubles dlrs 875 million, 700 million rubles dlrs 43 million less than expected', 112.0809270310986], ["The government wants to reverse this trend by raising taxes for oil and gas companies, but the idea is expected to meet sharp resistance in the lower house of Russia's parliament, which wants to cut tax rates, Pochinok said", 236.11109192018287], ["   President Leonid Kuchma called Friday for corrections'' to Ukraine's program of market reforms, but pledged that reforms would continue", 149.1013459241374], ["Kuchma did not elaborate in his comments to a group of Ukrainian economists, saying only that the changes were necessary because of the country's economic problems", 174.10221652536518], ['Kuchma urged the economists to come up with recommendations before a national meeting of economists in November, the Interfax news agency reported', 157.09956922948456], ['Ukraine has suffered economic problems since the 1991 collapse of the Soviet Union and it has been especially hard hit by the financial crisis in neighboring Russia, its main trading partner', 207.0901936383778], ['The Russian crisis has hurt bilateral trade, caused the Ukrainian currency to fall and led to a withdrawal of investors from Ukraine', 145.071856035105], ['In recent months, Kuchma has implemented some economic reforms by decree, prompting the International Monetary Fund to release the first installment of a long-awaited dlrs 22 billion loan', 207.09805202368497], ['Many reforms, however, remain stalled', 40.03218327686331], ['National Bank chairman Viktor Yushchenko was in Washington this week for consultations with IMF officials', 118.04781860147709], ['Yushchenko has warned that the bank would not spend its dwindling reserves to support the hryvna currency, but has avoided comments on the currency in recent days', 171.10856154335366], ['Kuchma met Friday with Yushchenko, Prime Minister Valery Pustovoitenko and other senior officials to discuss ways to stabilize the hryvna', 154.1091220859013], ["The government's press service said they focused on possible ways to keep the hryvna under 35 to the US dollar through the end of the year", 147.07430949788568], ['The hryvna has been trading at 34 to the dollar in recent days but trading has been limited', 98.08963167889178], ['There are wide expectations in Ukraine that the hryvna will fall even further, and Ukrainians have been stocking up on food, clothing and household goods to save their fast-devaluing money', 199.1141316412768]]
